<DocsLayout title="Project 8: The Production Pipeline" description="Build an event management and ticketing platform with CI/CD, feature flags, monitoring, and incident response.">
  <h1 class="mb-2">Project 8: The Production Pipeline</h1>
  <p class="text-xl text-primary font-medium mb-6">"I can run a full CI/CD pipeline with staging, production, feature flags, and zero-downtime deploys."</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll build</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">An event management and ticketing platform for SurfCoast Events — Liam's surf competition and beach festival business along Victoria's surf coast (Bells Beach, Torquay, Lorne, Apollo Bay). Event listings with dates and locations, ticket sales (Stripe from P4), attendee check-in via QR codes, and an event-day live dashboard showing real-time attendance and sales. Weather integration using the Bureau of Meteorology API.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What's new (the +1)</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Operations. Until now, you've built systems and deployed them. This project is about <strong class="text-text">operating</strong> a system — keeping it alive, measuring it, responding when things go wrong, and releasing features safely.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Feature flags decouple deployment from release. You deploy code to production with features turned off, then enable them when ready — for specific users, for your team, or for everyone. Prometheus collects metrics. Grafana visualises them. PagerDuty wakes you up when something breaks. Load testing with k6 proves the system can handle event-day traffic before the event happens. And incident response runbooks give you a checklist for when things go wrong at 2am.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Why this matters:</strong> Shipping code is not the finish line. Operating the system is. Feature flags let you ship without risk. Monitoring tells you if the system is healthy. Alerting tells you when it's not. Load testing proves it can handle the worst case. Incident runbooks give you a plan when everything else fails. This is the difference between "I can build it" and "I can run it."</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What success looks like</h2>
  <Checklist items={[
    "A CI/CD pipeline deploys to staging automatically and to production with manual approval",
    "Feature flags control feature visibility — deploy and enable are separate actions",
    "Prometheus collects application metrics and Grafana displays them on dashboards",
    "PagerDuty alerts fire when error rate or latency exceeds thresholds",
    "k6 load tests simulate 500 concurrent users and the system stays responsive",
    "An incident response runbook exists and has been walked through on the extension scenario",
    "Liam can sell tickets, check in attendees via QR code, and see a live event-day dashboard",
  ]} />

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll learn</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Implement feature flags with Unleash (or LaunchDarkly) for safe, incremental releases</li>
    <li>Collect application metrics with Prometheus and build Grafana dashboards</li>
    <li>Configure PagerDuty (or OpsGenie) alerting for production incidents</li>
    <li>Write and run load tests with k6 to validate performance under pressure</li>
    <li>Write incident response runbooks for production emergencies</li>
    <li>Specify and verify non-functional requirements (latency, throughput, availability)</li>
    <li>Operate a blue/green deployment pipeline with rollback capability</li>
    <li>Practise trunk-based development with feature flags instead of long-lived branches</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Tech stack</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>React + FastAPI + RDS PostgreSQL (multi-AZ)</li>
    <li>EC2 behind ALB, provisioned with Terraform</li>
    <li>Prometheus + Grafana for metrics and dashboards</li>
    <li>Feature flags: Unleash (self-hosted) or LaunchDarkly (free tier)</li>
    <li>PagerDuty (free tier) for alerting</li>
    <li>k6 for load testing</li>
    <li>GitHub Actions CI/CD with environment approvals</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Completed <a href="/web-dev/projects/7">Project 7</a></li>
    <li>Familiarity with Terraform and AWS from Projects 6-7</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Estimated time</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">3 weeks. The planning artifacts follow the established pattern. The operational tooling — feature flags, Prometheus, Grafana, PagerDuty, k6, and incident runbooks — adds significant setup and learning time beyond application development.</p>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
